\begin_layout Section
Identification of items for status consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simple regression model to understand the consumption on status items
 can be formulated as the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
s & =\beta_{1}\phi(\sum_{i\in B}q_{i},\boldsymbol{q})+\beta_{2}z+\epsilon\label{eq:main_regression}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the relevant consumption measure for the identified status categories
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The equation does not relax the earlier assertion of there not being any
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

status
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 category of commodoties.
 The equation is only used to seek the parameters associated with an item
 that contribute to the status it carries.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the consumption on an item 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q}$
\end_inset


\series default
 being the vector of quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 ) in the basket 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a function and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 denotes the household characteristics.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:main_regression"

\end_inset

 can only represent consumption items whose total costs can be added up
 to the dependent variable 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 As we don't have the cost for assets (nor their quantities or the quantities
 of any non-food item) the relative expenditure between assets and consumption
 cannot be explained using the above model.
 Our attempt to use asset-ownership as a control variable in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:main_regression"

\end_inset

 involves using a total ownership score - which is obtained by summing up
 the different assets owned within a category of assets.
 The asset control variable thus obtained can help determine whether asset
 ownership changes consumption on items in 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our assumption that a consumer doesn't compromise tastes amongst the functional
 categories requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 be split between functional categories.
 This means that the Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:main_regression"

\end_inset

 needs to be viewed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
s_{c\in\mathscr{C}} & =\beta_{1,c\in\mathscr{C}}\phi_{c}(\sum_{i\in B}q_{i},\boldsymbol{q})+\beta_{2,c\in\mathscr{C}}z+\epsilon
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 is the set of categories encompassing a category 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 To reiterate, we avoid viewing a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

status category
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:main_regression"

\end_inset

 because of our claim that amongst available items to buy, a consumer does
 not look for a status item per se (much less so in the developing countries
 where status is derived mostly from assets owned and quality of consumption).
 Even in the developed countries, a survey cannot unequivocally rank high
 quality food consumption lower or higher than the ownership of a sports-watch
 on a visibility or status scale.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the model we adopt for measurement of status consumption, we don't consider
 visibility to matter at a level finer than the broad consumption categories
 of food, energy, transport, personal care, social functions and housing.
 Therefore, while a consumer may find food consumption less visible overall
 than energy, we don't recognise a difference in visibility between mangoes
 and spam as relevant for status utility to the consumer.
 The differences in price and in perceived quality-of-life between consuming
 these two options are what motivate the consumer - not the sense of visibility.
 These factors are measured with the price differences within the items
 in a category and the substitution between consumption and assets for similar
 needs.
 The Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:status_dimensions"

\end_inset

 details this view of status consumption
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Notice that education - which is acquired over long-term - is viewed as
 an asset.
 Notice also that we consider it impossible to overspend on public transport
 to substitute for not owning a car.
 Hence there is no status advantage derived by overspending on public transport
 as consumption.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 As shown in the table, visibility has no role to play other than the weight
 consumers collectively put on the widely defined categories of food, energy,
 personal care, social functions, transport and housing.
 The consumers differentiate themselves from others in their social surrounding
 by buying more newer, higher priced items as well as overspending on consumptio
n categories that help them remain in the asset ownership club (the latter
 being the justification of consumption remaining in the same functional
 category).
\end_layout

