\begin_layout Standard
A clear limitation of the model is that even though our assumption of separabili
ty of categories of consumpation does not permit so, a consumer may overspend
 on more than one categories two compensate for another.
 In other words, a consumer who doesn't own a house may overspend on both
 carpets and weddings - even though this behaviour goes against our assumption
 of separability of these categories.
 However, as we do assume separability of categories in our current context,
 a one-to-one relation between the category of assets and the corresponding
 consumption category - which the consumer may overspend on - does follow
 as a consequence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Data Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dependent variable is the proportion of the group to the total expenditure.
 Comparing proportion of energy expenditures for example, the dependent
 variable is ratio of the expenditure on kerosene to the expenditure on
 gas and electricity i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\frac{q_{gas}+q_{electricity}+q_{charcoal}}{q_{electricity}+q_{gas}+q_{kerosene}+q_{charcoal}}$
\end_inset

 .
 This ratio can also be seen as a the budget ratio for expensive options
 calculated with respect to the total expenditure in the energy category.
 The control variables for Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:main_regression"

\end_inset

 are assets owned, total expenditure, occupation, education and the household
 size.
 Since the households using just kerosene (and no higher priced options)
 is quite high, one may use a Heckman selection to correct the bias imposed
 due to lack of electricity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The categorisation of all items is presented in the Table.
 Relying on the separability assumption, the two-state budgeting approach
 can make the categorisation of some items appear less justified.
 Categorising mosquito net as housing related product does appear to be
 a stretch and it is made worse by the usage on such items being driven
 by differences in climate across the population being surveyed.
 Since a model of demand only attempts to understand the consumer choice
 against the given options, it seems apt to consider items that are driven
 by random incidents (e.g.
 theft, ) in a misc category.
 Extreme supply side expenses (e.g.
 water, electricity) present a similar problem with demand analysis - requiring
 us to ensure that the lack of availability of electricity (or a similar
 commodity) in a locality is not viewed as the consumer's lack of preference
 towards it in the locality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For items where compensation with expenditure is relevant, the budget ratio
 is calculated against total expenditure while for items where we wish to
 inspect the preference of expensive varieties of the item, the budget ratio
 is calculated with expenditure in the category as the total expenditure
 (in accordance with the separability assumption).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a proper interpretation of costs, we must revisit the discussion on
 wholesale purchases - the presence of which might might skew our analyses.
 Since consumers buy wholesale of more than one items together - we look
 for instances where group of items bought with extremely high costs.
 Whenever the group is not found, the data can be ignored.
 This is necessary before an analysis is performed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For personal products, we need to exclude extreme values.
 We don't find that the assets matter so much for personal products.
 Assets move together with expenditure on personal products (or that the
 so-called assets are no different from the expenditure items).
  
\end_layout

