reference "tab:status_dimensions"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the separability of categories was to be relaxed, we may consider a cost-scal
e of assets and consumption where assets and consumption can be ordered
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $personal\ products<carpets<jewelry<...<home$
\end_inset

.
 Arguing that the consumers compensate for jewelry with personal products
 and in turn compensate with jewelry for home and so on, we can consider
 an matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Psi}_{m\times m}$
\end_inset

 that denotes the status advantage of every pair of consumption and asset
 items (
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 being the total number of assets and consumptions) .
 The status utility may thus look like 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline}
u_{s}=(AF_{food}\times\lambda_{food}+AF_{energy}\times\lambda_{energy}+...)\\
+\Psi(watches,house)\times q_{watches}+\Psi(personal\ products,jewelry)\times q_{personal\ products}+...\\
=\boldsymbol{AF}\times\boldsymbol{\lambda}+\boldsymbol{\Psi}\times\boldsymbol{q}
\end{multline}

\end_inset

 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Psi}$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 (triangular) matrix representing the status advantage to a consumer from
 an item's consumption which is in compensation for lack of a corresponding
 asset (
\begin_inset Formula $m=$
\end_inset

